    id="summary"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Plain-English summary"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      In plain English
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      The Argument in 150 Words
    </h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa is trying to run the foreign and security policy of a
      top-twenty state on the budget of an upper-middle-income economy that is
      shrinking on a per-capita basis. The country has a serious set of
      strategic doctrines — a 2025 National Security Strategy with eight
      pillars, a four-interest national-interest framework, and a long-term
      defence plan. But the economy that funds them is growing too slowly to
      keep up. The defence budget sits 43 per cent below its own stated
      baseline. Unemployment is above 32 per cent. The diplomatic profile is
      bigger than the economic base can carry.
    </p>
    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      This article reconstructs the country's grand strategy from its layered
      doctrines, weighs it against four interpretive lenses and six failure
      modes, and proposes a strategy aligned to the country's actual endowments.
      It then maps every pillar of the GovCompass Reform Agenda to the
      grand-strategic component it is designed to deliver.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 1: Introduction & Conceptual Foundation -->
  <section
    id="introduction"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Introduction and conceptual foundation"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 1
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      The Arithmetic of South African Grand Strategy
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Start with the numbers, because they discipline everything else. South
      Africa is running the foreign and security policy of a top-twenty state on
      <a
        href="/articles/eg-1-1-the-seven-thousand-rand-economy"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold"
        >a roughly $400-billion economy</a
      ><sup class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-6" id="ref-6" class="hover:underline">[6]</a></sup
      >. Unemployment sits above 32 per cent on the narrow definition and past
      40 per cent on the broad one. The Department of Defence's own baseline
      puts the SANDF (South African National Defence Force) at R98.3 billion a
      year; the 2025–26 allocation is R57.2 billion — a structural deficit of 43
      per cent<sup class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-1" id="ref-1" class="hover:underline">[1]</a></sup
      >. The 2025 National Security Strategy declares eight security pillars.
      The 2022 Framework Document on the National Interest names four core
      interests. The pending Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy — "Journey to
      Greatness" — proposes a 1.5-per-cent-of-GDP defence floor. Reserve Bank
      projections keep per-capita income stagnant for the rest of the decade.
      Strategic ambition and economic base are not in alignment, and the gap is
      the subject of this article.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary"
        >Paul Kennedy's thesis is the mechanism that animates the analysis:
        great powers decline when strategic commitments outrun the economic base
        on which they rest.</strong
      > South Africa is not a great power, but the principle scales — a state's commitments
      either match its base or, in time, hollow it out. The wider conceptual lineage
      supplies the vocabulary: Liddell Hart on strategy extending beyond the battlefield
      into the peace that follows; Luttwak on Roman grand strategy as an adaptive
      system rather than a fixed doctrine; John Lewis Gaddis on the calculated relationship
      of means to large ends; Colin Gray on the direction and use made of any and
      all the assets of a security community for the political purposes it has adopted.
      <strong class="text-text-primary"
        >Across the tradition, one discipline holds: grand strategy is what
        happens when a state refuses to treat its military, economic,
        diplomatic, and domestic choices as separate conversations and instead
        asks how they add up.</strong
      >
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A country that takes its grand strategy seriously has to confront the
      arithmetic.
      <strong class="text-text-primary"
        >A country that does not ends up with a doctrinal stack describing a
        world the state cannot afford, a defence force it cannot fund, and a
        diplomatic posture whose costs it cannot absorb.</strong
      >
      What follows is an attempt to bring doctrinal ambition and economic arithmetic
      into the same conversation — not to diminish the former, but to specify what
      it would take to fund it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The piece proceeds in four moves. The first reconstructs South Africa's
      grand strategy from the doctrinal stack — the constitutional, strategic,
      foreign-policy, defence, and development tiers that together answer the
      grand-strategic question, even though no single document carries the
      title. The second evaluates that strategy through the classical
      Ends–Ways–Means triad, through four interpretive lenses, and through a
      risk register naming the six most visible gaps between doctrine and
      delivery. The third proposes an endowment-aligned alternative — a strategy
      built upward from the country's actual resources rather than downward from
      inherited ambition. The fourth shows how the GovCompass Reform Agenda is
      the domestic execution layer without which either strategy remains
      performative.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The tone is analytical rather than advocatory. The goal is to give the
      reader the apparatus to judge for themselves whether the country's
      strategic commitments and its economic base are in alignment — and, if
      they are not, what realignment would require. Grand strategy belongs to
      citizens as much as to cabinets. The citizens who understand it are the
      ones who can hold the cabinet to it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: Doctrinal Stack -->
  <section
    id="doctrinal-stack"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="The doctrinal stack"
