    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      Reconstructing the Grand Strategy from Its Doctrinal Architecture
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa does not publish a single document titled "Grand Strategy."
      The phrase appears in academic commentary and in think-tank analysis, but
      no statutory instrument, presidential proclamation, or white paper gathers
      the ambition under that heading. This absence is not an oversight; it is a
      feature of how the state has chosen to articulate its strategic purpose.
      The grand strategy must instead be reconstructed from a layered doctrinal
      stack, each layer operating at a different altitude, each layer binding on
      the layers below it.
    </p>

    <DoctrinalStack />

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The constitutional tier sits at the top. The Constitution of 1996 —
      especially Section 198, which opens the chapter on security services —
      defines security as inseparable from human dignity, equality, and freedom.
      "National security must reflect the resolve of South Africans, as
      individuals and as a nation, to live as equals, to live in peace and
      harmony, to be free from fear and want and to seek a better life." This
      formulation is not decorative. It binds every downstream strategic
      document to a values-first definition of security, one that treats
      developmental outcomes — not only territorial defence — as constitutive of
      national security itself. Few states' grand strategies are anchored this
      deep in constitutional values. South Africa's is.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Below the constitutional tier sits the strategic tier. The National
      Security Strategy 2024–2029 (NSS), publicly released on 15 July 2025, is
      the central document here. Its release marked the first transparent
      publication of core intelligence doctrine in South African history — a
      posture shift from the classified tradition inherited from the State
      Security Agency era. The NSS articulates eight security pillars, maps a
      threat landscape, and situates security within the developmental mandate
      of the state. Alongside the NSS sit the National Intelligence Estimate for
      the 2019–2024 period, which inventoried threats to the economy,
      territorial integrity, state authority, citizen well-being, and the global
      environment, and the National Intelligence Priorities that cascade
      downward to operational intelligence tasking.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The foreign-policy tier articulates how the state operates externally. The
      2011 White Paper "Building a Better World: The Diplomacy of Ubuntu"
      remains the principal articulation of diplomatic philosophy — humanity in
      connection, peaceful conflict resolution, Global South solidarity. The
      Department of International Relations and Cooperation (DIRCO) Strategic
      Plan 2025–2030 translates that philosophy into a programme of activity:
      economic diplomacy, multilateral positioning, consular services, and
      development cooperation through the South African Development Partnership
      Agency (SADPA). The 2022 Framework Document on the National Interest,
      adopted by Cabinet in the wake of academic and policy debate over how
      South Africa defines its own interests, names four — Survival, Prosperity,
      Identity, and Influence — and provides the conceptual hinge between
      foreign-policy philosophy and security doctrine.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The defence tier specifies how force is organised and used. The 1996 White
      Paper on Defence established the post-1994 normative framework; the 1998
      and 2015 Defence Reviews updated force design and capability planning; and
      the pending Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy 2025–2055, known by its
      internal title "Journey to Greatness," proposes a multi-decade trajectory
      toward a defence expenditure floor of 1.5 per cent of GDP. As of late 2025
      the Strategy still awaits a Special National Security Council session
      before adoption — a delay that itself is doctrinally informative, in that
      the force-evolution layer remains suspended while the fiscal and political
      conditions for its adoption are negotiated.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The development tier anchors the domestic limb of the grand strategy. The
      National Development Plan — Vision 2030 (NDP), adopted in 2012 — remains
      the reference framework for every department's planning cycle, even as its
      2030 target date approaches without the growth and employment outcomes it
      promised. The NDP is the explicit bridge between the foreign-policy vision
      of "a better South Africa, in a better Africa, in a better world" and the
      domestic machinery that is supposed to deliver it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Why the stacked-doctrine approach matters analytically is that it forces
      the analyst to read coherence vertically rather than horizontally. The
      question is not whether any one layer is internally sound, but whether the
      layers point in the same direction. A NSS that names economic security as
      a pillar and a NDP that has not produced economic security are in vertical
      tension. A White Paper on Foreign Policy that invokes Ubuntu values and a
      BRICS partnership that includes authoritarian states under investigation
      by the International Criminal Court are in vertical tension. Vertical
      tension is not a failure; it is the material from which grand strategy is
      negotiated. But it must be named.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The doctrinal stack is not read in isolation. A substantial think-tank
      overlay provides independent scrutiny — the Institute for Security
      Studies, the South African Institute of International Affairs, the
      Brenthurst Foundation's archive of developmental-state analysis, the
      Belfer Center's work on middle-power positioning, and the academic
      journals (the South African Journal of International Affairs, African
      Security Review, Strategic Review for Southern Africa) that provide the
      peer-reviewed counterweight to government doctrine. The reader who wants
      to understand South Africa's grand strategy has to read both the stack and
      the overlay. The sections that follow do so.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3: Ends -->
  <section
    id="ends"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="The ends of grand strategy"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 3
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      The Ends: What South Africa Seeks to Achieve
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Ends of South Africa's grand strategy are articulated at three nested
      levels. At the widest level sits the overarching vision: "A better South
      Africa, in a better Africa, in a better world." The phrase recurs, almost
      verbatim, in the 2011 White Paper on Foreign Policy, the National
      Development Plan, the DIRCO Strategic Plan 2025–2030, and the National
      Security Strategy. Its repetition is not rhetorical filler. It encodes a
      specific doctrinal choice: domestic transformation, continental renewal,
      and the reform of the global order are treated as one integrated programme
      rather than three separable objectives. The constitutional values that
      bind domestic policy — dignity, equality, non-racialism, the primacy of
      the rule of law — are the same values that are projected into the African
      agenda and into the multilateral reform agenda. The vision is, in its own
      terms, constitutionally rooted and values-driven.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The middle level specifies the four core national interests, codified in
      the 2022 Framework Document on the National Interest and echoed through
      the NSS. Survival covers sovereignty, territorial integrity, and the
      protection of the constitutional order — the preconditions without which
      no other interest can be pursued. Prosperity covers growth, employment,
      the reduction of poverty and inequality, and the productive base from
      which the state draws its resources; it is the domestic economic content
      of the national interest, usually condensed in political discourse into
      the phrase "the triple challenge" of poverty, inequality, and
      unemployment. Identity covers the constitutional values, social cohesion,
      and the Ubuntu tradition that the state treats as its normative signature.
      Influence covers the voice of South Africa — and, more broadly, of Africa
      and the Global South — in the forums that shape global rules. The four
      interests are presented as coequal; in practice, as later sections will
      show, they are not.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The narrowest level is the NSS's eight security pillars, which
      operationalise the Ends across non-overlapping security domains. Each
      pillar names a field of operational activity and carries downstream
      planning obligations.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 mb-6">
      {
        nssPillars.map((p) => (
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
            <div class="flex items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
              <span class="font-heading text-xs font-bold text-compass-green">
                Pillar {p.n}
              </span>
              <span class="font-heading text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary">
                {p.title}
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">{p.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The pillars are structured to be MECE — mutually exclusive (no two pillars
      cover the same ground) and collectively exhaustive (between them they
      cover every security domain). Public Security is the protection of persons
      and communities from crime and disorder; Territorial Integrity is the
      protection of borders, airspace, and the exclusive economic zone;
      Sovereignty Projection is the credible capacity to defend the
      constitutional order and project influence externally; Economic Security
      is the productive base on which every other pillar rests; Cyber and
      Information Security is the defence of digital and informational
      infrastructure; Technology and Innovation is the indigenous capability in
      strategic technologies; Environmental and Natural Resource Security is
      water, food, energy, and climate resilience treated as security concerns;
      Cultural Security is social cohesion and the identity dimension of
      nation-building.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The "negative" of the Ends is supplied by the National Intelligence
      Estimate's five threat axes: threats to the economy, to territorial
      integrity, to state authority, to citizen well-being, and threats
      emanating from the global environment. The inverse mapping is deliberate.
      If Economic Security is a pillar, then threats to the economy —
      grey-listing, tariff retaliation, state capture of fiscal institutions —
      are counted as security threats, not merely as economic news. If
      Sovereignty Projection is a pillar, then threats to state authority —
      organised criminal networks, illicit financial flows, the collapse of the
      criminal-justice pipeline — are counted as strategic rather than
      departmental. The inversion is the bridge by which the Estimate translates
      into intelligence tasking.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Are the Ends internally coherent? At the level of stated ambition, broadly
      yes. The vision is clear, the four interests are well-specified, and the
      eight pillars are domain-complete. The values framework does real work —
      the Rome Statute obligations, the commitment to international humanitarian
      law, the Ubuntu tradition — in a way that differentiates South Africa from
      non-aligned peers whose strategic doctrine is more transactional.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      Are the Ends realistic, given the state's current economic position? That
      is a different question, and it is where the doctrinal stack encounters
      the arithmetic. A state with a ~$400 billion GDP, a narrow tax base, a
      declining per-capita income, and a military budget 43 per cent below its
      own stated baseline cannot simultaneously deliver all eight pillars at the
      level the NSS implies. The Ends are aspirational in the literal sense:
      they describe what the state seeks, not what it has yet built the base to
      afford. The later sections — on Means, on Risks, and on the
      endowment-aligned alternative — take up the implications of that gap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4: Ways -->
  <section
    id="ways"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Strategic posture and ways"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 4
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      The Ways: Converting Interests into Action
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Four distinctive Ways define South Africa's strategic posture. They are
      analytically separable but operationally interlinked, and each has a body
      of doctrinal and academic literature clarifying its scope. Together they
      form the repertoire by which the state attempts to convert its stated
      interests into external action.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      1. Active Non-Alignment and Strategic Autonomy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Active non-alignment is not neutrality. It is the deliberate refusal of
      bloc allegiance combined with active coalition-building across blocs.
      Minister of International Relations Ronald Lamola's September 2025
      articulation — that South Africa's foreign policy is governed by principle
      rather than camp, and that the country retains the right to vote its
      conscience in every multilateral forum — is the most recent authoritative
      statement of the doctrine. The Hague Group co-chairmanship, the ICJ case
      against Israel, and the measured handling of Ukraine are the proof-points
      most often cited. The academic literature, particularly the work of Otto
      and Nagar in the South African Journal of International Affairs, has
      refined the concept further as "negotiated institutional accommodation" —
      a posture sustained through flexible legal interpretation rather than open
      defiance of international norms, as illustrated by the 2023 BRICS summit's
      handling of the Putin arrest-warrant dilemma, where the state resolved a
      constitutional conflict through a procedural mechanism rather than a
      political confrontation.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      2. Pan-African Agency and the Regional Anchor Role
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Africa is doctrinally "the centre" of South African foreign and security
      policy. The 2011 White Paper, the NSS, and the DIRCO Strategic Plan all
      position Pan-African agency as the first-order Way. Operational
      expressions are numerous: Southern African Development Community (SADC)
      and African Union (AU) Standby Force support; the SADC Mission in the DRC
      (SAMIDRC) deployment in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo; the
      championing of the African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA); the
      long-running push for a permanent African seat on the United Nations
      Security Council; the projection of peace-mediation credentials from
      Lesotho and Burundi in the past to Sudan and the Great Lakes in the
      present. The Way asserts that South Africa cannot be a credible global
      actor if it is not first a credible regional actor, and that continental
      integration is both a developmental and a security project.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      3. Ubuntu Diplomacy and Values-Based Norm Entrepreneurship
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The 2011 White Paper's diplomatic signature is Ubuntu —
      humanity-as-interconnection — translated into peaceful conflict
      resolution, Global South solidarity, and normative positioning in
      multilateral forums. South Africa projects itself as a norm entrepreneur:
      the state that takes the Palestinian cause to the ICJ, the state that
      carries the decolonial agenda into the G20, the state whose Constitutional
      Court judgments on dignity and equality are cited in foreign
      jurisdictions. The critique, articulated most sharply by Brooks Spector
      through SAIIA commentary and echoed by the ISS, is that the posture is
      normatively aspirational but operationally thin: the values rhetoric is
      not matched by a commensurate delivery apparatus, and the state's own
      domestic record on human-rights indicators complicates the external
      projection.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      4. Multi-Aligned Multilateralism
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The fourth Way is the deliberate stacking of memberships. BRICS, the G20,
      the India–Brazil– South Africa Dialogue Forum (IBSA), the Non-Aligned
      Movement (NAM), the Commonwealth, the AU, SADC, the European Union
      Strategic Partnership, the rotating UN Security Council seat — the state
      holds a portfolio of memberships unmatched by any other middle power. The
      portfolio is used to leverage every forum for Global South agenda-setting
      while maintaining Western market access. The Belfer Center has
      characterised this in a November 2025 analysis as "coordinated
      multi-alignment" — not a confusion of affiliations but a calculated
      attempt to extract informational and bargaining advantage from each forum
      simultaneously.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Are the Four Ways Consistent?
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The four Ways are not obviously contradictory, but they generate real
      tensions that the state has to manage in real time. Active non-alignment
      and Ubuntu values constrain behaviour in BRICS forums where partners do
      not share the values. Pan-African agency and multi-aligned multilateralism
      compete for finite diplomatic attention and budget. Norm entrepreneurship
      on the Palestinian question sits beside relative silence on Sudan and
      parts of the Sahel — an inconsistency SAIIA has named directly. The 2023
      Putin–ICC episode is the illustrative case: the state simultaneously
      maintained BRICS solidarity (Way 4), honoured its Rome Statute obligations
      (Way 3), preserved Pan-African standing (Way 2), and refused bloc pressure
      from both sides (Way 1) — through a procedural accommodation that, while
      legally workable, drew criticism from every constituency at once.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The honest reading is that the four Ways are simultaneously operable only
      when the state has sufficient diplomatic, economic, and military depth to
      absorb the tensions they generate. As the economic base narrows and the
      military instrument degrades, the bandwidth for managing contradiction
      narrows with it. The Ways do not then fail; they become more expensive to
      sustain, and the trade-offs that were previously invisible become visible.
      Section 7 returns to this dynamic under the heading of Risks.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5: Means -->
  <section
    id="means"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="The instruments of national power"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 5
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      The Means: Instruments of National Power — A DIME Assessment
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The DIME framework — Diplomatic, Informational, Military, Economic — is
      the standard analytic grid for assessing the instruments of national
      power. Applied to South Africa it produces a portrait whose unevenness is
      itself the most important finding. The state is diplomatically overweight
      and militarily and economically hollow, and the mismatch between the
      instruments defines the strategic problem.
    </p>

    <!-- DIME scorecard -->
    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 mb-8"
      aria-label="DIME scorecard summary"
    >
      {
        dimeScorecard.map((d) => (
          <div class={`border-l-4 rounded-r-lg p-4 ${dimeToneStyles[d.tone]}`}>
            <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-1 gap-2">
              <span class="font-heading text-sm font-bold text-text-primary">
                {d.instrument}
              </span>
              <span class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-text-secondary">
                {d.verdict}
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
              {d.summary}
            </p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Diplomatic
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa maintains approximately 120 diplomatic missions abroad<sup
        class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-3" id="ref-3" class="hover:underline">[3]</a></sup
      >
      — one of the larger footprints in the Global South. The DIRCO Strategic Plan
      2025–2030 centralises economic diplomacy as a principal function, shifting missions
      from representational toward outcome-based commercial roles. The state holds
      a membership portfolio unmatched by its peers: BRICS, G20, IBSA, NAM, Commonwealth,
      AU, SADC, EU Strategic Partnership, and rotational UN Security Council seats.
      It has exercised convening power at scale — the 2023 BRICS summit, the 2025
      G20 presidency, the 2025 SA–EU summit — and maintains SADPA as a development-assistance
      channel. The diplomatic instrument is the most capable arm of national power,
      and its capability is the principal source of the state's outsized strategic
      profile relative to its economic weight.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Informational
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The informational instrument is mixed. On the asset side, the Ubuntu
      narrative functions as soft power, the G20 messaging on an equitable
      international order has landed, and the NSS's own publication was itself a
      transparency-as-soft-power move. On the weakness side, NSS Pillar 5 —
      Cyber and Information Security — is explicitly flagged by the state as
      under-developed. The country's counter-disinformation capability is
      limited, information-space sovereignty is weak, and cybersecurity posture
      lags the threat profile. The gap is not for want of awareness; it is for
      want of investment and coordinated architecture.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Military
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The South African National Defence Force is the most degraded instrument
      in the portfolio, and the structural numbers are stark. The baseline
      budget requirement, as estimated by the Department of Defence itself, is
      approximately R98.3 billion; the 2025–26 allocation is R57.2 billion — a
      structural deficit of 43 per cent<sup class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-1" class="hover:underline">[1]</a></sup
      >. More than 60 per cent of that constrained allocation is consumed by
      personnel costs, leaving operational and capital budgets residual.
      Force-structure data tell the same story. Of 26 Gripen fighters on the
      books, roughly 12 are reported operational. The C-130BZ transport fleet,
      the backbone of strategic airlift, is largely not airworthy. The submarine
      arm is non-functional. The frigate force has, by public accounts, one
      operational vessel at any given time<sup class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-2" id="ref-2" class="hover:underline">[2]</a></sup
      >.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Operational consequences followed in early 2025 when the SAMIDRC
      deployment suffered the loss of 14 SANDF soldiers in the eastern DRC — an
      engagement that exposed deficits in air cover,
      intelligence-surveillance-reconnaissance, and medical-evacuation capacity.
      The governance collapse of Denel, the state defence-industrial prime, has
      removed domestic production of several systems the SANDF depends on. The
      2015 Defence Review had set a force-design trajectory oriented around
      Special Operations and a Medium Combat Forces capability; current funding
      supports neither. The pending Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy 2025–2055
      targets a 1.5 per cent of GDP defence floor that Minister Motshekga has
      publicly conceded will take "many years" to reach. The instrument, in
      short, is insufficient for the Sovereignty Projection pillar the NSS
      claims.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Economic
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The economic instrument presents the largest portfolio of latent strengths
      and active vulnerabilities. Strengths: two-ocean geography astride the
      Cape route, the world's deepest reserves of platinum-group metals,
      manganese, and chromium, deep capital markets and a sophisticated
      financial and legal services sector, and a bilateral BRICS trade
      relationship estimated at roughly $50 billion in 2022<sup
        class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-4" id="ref-4" class="hover:underline">[4]</a></sup
      >. The Department of Trade, Industry and Competition's economic-diplomacy
      mechanism and DIRCO's 2025–2030 reorientation together constitute a
      commercial-diplomacy architecture that, on paper, is credible.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A fourth and under-counted strand of the economic endowment is the
      hydrocarbon position. The 2019 Brulpadda and 2020 Luiperd gas-condensate
      discoveries in the Outeniqua Basin off Mossel Bay are estimated, on
      operator data, to contain in the order of one billion barrels of oil
      equivalent — sufficient, if developed, to extend the operating life of the
      PetroSA gas-to- liquids facility and to seed a domestic feedstock for
      combined-cycle gas turbines on the southern Cape coast. The onshore Karoo
      holds an unconventional shale-gas resource whose scale is contested but
      whose lower-bound estimates remain materially significant; coal-bed
      methane in KwaZulu-Natal and the Free State adds a further increment. None
      of these resources is producing at scale today, and each carries a
      distinct regulatory, environmental, and fiscal- terms question — but the
      cumulative position is that South Africa is energy-rich on paper in ways
      its current grid and refining configuration does not reflect.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The regional supply geometry compounds the point. The Republic of
      Mozambique Pipeline Company (ROMPCO) line from Mozambique's Pande and
      Temane fields has, since 2004, delivered roughly 180 petajoules a year of
      natural gas<sup class="text-compass-green"
        ><a href="#fig-5" id="ref-5" class="hover:underline">[5]</a></sup
      >
      into South African industry — principally Sasol's Secunda complex and a cluster
      of gas-fired industrial users; the field decline profile creates a "gas cliff"
      in the late-2020s that domestic policy has not yet resolved. Mozambique's Rovuma
      Basin LNG developments — TotalEnergies' Mozambique LNG and ENI's Coral South
      — sit on continental gas reserves among the largest discovered this century,
      and offer a long-duration import channel through proposed LNG regasification
      terminals at Coega, Richards Bay, and Saldanha. Namibia's Orange Basin oil discoveries
      — Venus, Graff, and Mopane — make SADC a prospective petroleum exporter for
      the first time, with secondary effects on logistics, refining, and bunkering
      at South African ports. Angola's established oil sector and Zimbabwe's onshore
      gas at Muzarabani round out a regional hydrocarbon map that did not exist a
      decade ago. The strategic point is that South Africa's energy posture cannot
      be assessed as a closed national system; it is part of a SADC hydrocarbon basin
      whose terms of access are an instrument of national power in their own right.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Vulnerabilities: the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) grey-listing
      imposed reputational and operational costs on cross-border finance; the
      United States' 30 per cent reciprocal tariff imposed in August 2025
      removed a material share of the export advantage to the US market; the
      review of the African Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA, the US
      trade-preference programme that gives sub-Saharan African exports
      duty-free access to American markets) creates further uncertainty;
      state-owned enterprise (SOE) decay — Eskom, Transnet, and the
      <a
        href="/reform/articles/ra-4-1-fixing-water-and-sanitation"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold">water boards</a
      >
      — continues to degrade the network-industry base on which private investment
      depends. The economic instrument is potentially formidable; it is actually under-performing.
      The gap between potential and performance is the most consequential DIME finding,
      because it is the gap that funds — or fails to fund — every other instrument.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The DIME Judgement
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The portfolio is diplomatically overweight and militarily and economically
      hollow. That is the clear judgement. The diplomatic instrument is used,
      successfully, to extract strategic position that the economic and military
      instruments cannot earn. This extraction has limits. When the underlying
      base does not grow, the diplomatic premium erodes, and external actors
      price the mismatch — in tariff policy, in investment decisions, in the
      terms of bilateral deals — more sharply than they did a decade ago. The
      strategic task is not to trim the diplomatic instrument but to rebuild the
      economic base that gives it durable leverage.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 6: Perspectives -->
  <section
    id="perspectives"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Four interpretive perspectives"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 6
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      Four Lenses: How Different Constituencies Read the Strategy
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      No grand-strategic analysis is the analyst's alone. Four interpretive
      camps read South Africa's grand strategy, and the camps are mutually
      exclusive enough that distinguishing them is a precondition for thinking
      clearly about the doctrinal stack. This section presents each fairly and
      allows the reader to weigh them.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Official Government Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The NSS and DIRCO frame grand strategy as people-centred human security
      fused with active non-alignment. Minister of State Security Khumbudzo
      Ntshavheni cast the July 2025 release of the NSS as "democratic renewal"
      and as the culmination of a post-State-Capture transparency turn. The
      success metrics, as the government states them, are fidelity to the
      constitutional values framework, African agency in continental
      institutions, reform of the multilateral architecture to admit Global
      South voice, and domestic progress against the triple challenge. The
      official reading treats the doctrinal stack as internally coherent and
      treats delivery gaps as a problem of implementation rather than of
      doctrine.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Independent Think-Tank Mainstream
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Institute for Security Studies and the South African Institute of
      International Affairs together articulate the mainstream independent
      reading. Jakkie Cilliers's African Futures work at the ISS has argued that
      the architecture of the strategy is sound but undermined, first, by
      foreign-policy drift toward Russia that is not in the national interest;
      second, by DIRCO capacity decay that erodes the diplomatic instrument's
      effectiveness; and, third, by the failure to convert values-based
      positioning into tangible economic benefit — trade, investment, and
      growth. Foreign policy, on this reading, should be measured by commercial
      outcomes. Elizabeth Sidiropoulos and her colleagues at SAIIA, writing
      particularly on the G20 presidency, have argued that the strategy is
      coherent on norm entrepreneurship but suffers from inconsistency in
      application — moral rhetoric on Gaza that outpaces equivalent action on
      Sudan and the Sahel — and that the Global South's numerical majority in
      multilateral forums can only be converted into agenda-setting power
      through technical expertise and sustained working-group engagement,
      neither of which the state currently supplies at scale.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Contrarian and Reformist Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A distinct body of analysis — Greg Mills and Ray Hartley through the
      Brenthurst Foundation archive, the Belfer Center on middle-power
      positioning, and the opposition analytical traditions associated with the
      Democratic Alliance and Free SA — reads the grand-strategic problem as
      fundamentally economic. On this reading, without sustained growth in the
      five-per-cent range, all strategic ambition becomes unfunded rhetoric.
      Brenthurst's "Asian Aspiration" thesis urges emulation of East Asian
      developmental-state discipline — export orientation, skills formation,
      fiscal conservatism, and sustained political will behind productive
      sectors. The Belfer Center's November 2025 analysis placed South Africa in
      the ambitious-Global-South agenda-setter camp but concluded that the
      China-leaning tilt in non-alignment has generated costly retaliation,
      particularly from the United States. The DA's critique, presented during
      parliamentary debate on the NSS, characterises the document as ambitious
      on paper, under- resourced in practice, and vague on the trade-offs
      between competing pillars.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Military and Defence-Community Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      defenceWeb, the Stellenbosch Centre for Military Studies, and the Africa
      Center for Strategic Studies together articulate the defence-community
      reading. The consensus is that the NSS correctly identifies defence as a
      pillar but that the SANDF as currently resourced cannot execute the
      pillar. Moses Khanyile and his colleagues have highlighted the
      intelligence- surveillance-reconnaissance and early-warning gaps exposed
      by SAMIDRC. The Africa Center, in its 2019 analysis of the old classified
      NSS, argued that the secrecy itself prevented coherent cross-departmental
      use of the Strategy; the 2025 publication partially remedies this, but the
      remedy is informational and does not itself close the capability gap. The
      reading insists that doctrinal aspiration without force-structure
      investment is not strategy.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The four lenses do not converge on a single verdict; they converge on a
      single observation. The strategy's architecture is at most broadly
      coherent; its delivery is at best uneven; and the binding constraint
      across all four readings is the same — the economic base. Where the
      readings differ is on what weight to give the diplomatic achievements of
      the doctrine relative to the delivery gap at home. The next section names
      the delivery gap in six families.
    </p>
  </section>

