  <!-- Section 8: Alternative -->
  <section
    id="alternative"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Endowment-aligned alternative"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 8
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      Playing the Hand South Africa Actually Holds
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A grand strategy aligned to South Africa's actual endowments looks
      different from one inherited from doctrinal inertia. It is built upward
      from the resource base rather than downward from doctrinal ambition. The
      discipline is to ask, first, what the country actually holds, and, second,
      what strategy makes the best use of that hand over the
      fifteen-to-twenty-year window during which the demographic dividend
      remains open.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The endowment stack is well-defined. South Africa holds world-leading
      reserves of platinum-group metals, manganese, chromium, and vanadium — the
      precise inputs for electric- vehicle drivetrains, green-hydrogen
      production, grid-scale battery storage, and high-grade stainless steel.
      The country has the deepest capital markets and most sophisticated
      financial and legal services sector in Africa. Its two-ocean geography
      astride the Cape route makes it the natural logistics gateway to the SADC
      interior. Its population is young, but skills- mismatched in ways the
      <a
        href="/reform/articles/ra-2-1-fixing-basic-education"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold">education</a
      >
      and Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) systems have not
      closed. Residual but decayed industrial, rail, and port infrastructure provides
      a base from which reconstruction is feasible, not a starting point from scratch.
      Diplomatic credibility as a non-aligned middle power and BRICS member remains
      a genuine, if declining, asset. Taken together, the endowment stack suggests
      a specific strategic programme.
    </p>

    <EndowmentStack />

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Six mutually reinforcing pillars follow from the endowment analysis.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar A — Mineral-Led Green Industrialisation
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Indonesia-nickel and Chile-lithium playbooks offer a credible
      template. Both countries tied their raw-material export regimes to
      mandatory domestic beneficiation — refining, smelting, and
      higher-value-chain activity onshore — in exchange for continued access to
      international markets. South Africa can pursue the equivalent strategy for
      PGM fuel cells, manganese cathode materials, and vanadium flow batteries.
      This is the one sector where the country's endowments match
      twenty-first-century demand precisely, and the strategic value of the
      mineral base depreciates if it is captured only as raw-material rent.
      Green industrialisation is not an environmental preference; it is the
      fiscal foundation of the next twenty years.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar B — Energy Transition as Industrial Policy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Eskom crisis is the binding constraint on the entire endowment-aligned
      programme — and it is an opportunity, not only a liability. A credible
      energy-transition programme builds domestic solar, wind, and
      green-hydrogen manufacturing capability, co-locates production with PGM
      deposits to compress the supply chain, and treats decarbonisation as the
      vehicle for reindustrialisation. The Renewable Energy Independent Power
      Producer Procurement Programme (REIPPPP) provides a starting architecture;
      the Just Energy Transition (JET) Partnership provides a financing channel.
      The strategic question is whether the country uses the transition to build
      industry or merely to import green technology from manufacturers
      elsewhere. The answer determines whether the energy sector becomes a
      growth engine or a cost centre.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar C — Regional Hydrocarbon Bridge as Industrial Feedstock
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The energy transition is a multi-decade build-out, not a step-change. In
      the interim, gas — domestic and regional — is the bridge fuel that
      determines whether reindustrialisation has a feedstock or stalls for want
      of one. South Africa's hydrocarbon endowment, complemented by the Rovuma
      and Orange Basin discoveries on its border, gives the country a
      transitional-fuel position few peers possess. Brulpadda and Luiperd, if
      developed under fiscal terms that retain the upside onshore, extend the
      PetroSA gas-to-liquids facility's life and seed a southern-Cape
      gas-to-power cluster. Coal-bed methane in KwaZulu-Natal and the Free State
      offers a smaller but earlier-to-market increment. The Karoo unconventional
      resource sits on a different time-horizon and risk profile, and its
      development cannot be assumed; but it cannot be excluded from the
      strategic conversation a priori either, and the regulatory framework
      should be honest about that.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The regional dimension is where the leverage compounds. The ROMPCO
      pipeline can be repurposed and reverse-flowed to take Mozambican LNG
      inland from a Matola or Maputo regasification terminal; new South African
      LNG terminals at Coega, Richards Bay, and Saldanha can absorb Rovuma gas
      on long-duration contracts that anchor the Mozambican upstream and the
      South African midstream simultaneously. Supply diversification reduces
      single-source exposure to the Pande–Temane decline. Namibian crude
      offshore, refined onshore, becomes a credible replacement for the
      closed-down Cape coastal refining capacity. Treating SADC as a single
      hydrocarbon basin — with South Africa as the demand anchor, regulatory
      hub, and downstream beneficiator — converts geological adjacency into
      industrial leverage and a measurable share of the gas-cliff problem
      becomes solvable on infrastructure rather than diplomatic terms.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The pillar is not a substitute for the renewable build-out described under
      Pillar B; it is the load-bearing intermediate without which the transition
      collapses into a deindustrialised, import-dependent end-state. Gas-fired
      peaking capacity stabilises a grid that wind and solar cannot yet
      stabilise alone; gas-to-power displaces diesel open-cycle turbines that
      are currently the most expensive electricity on the system; gas-feedstock
      chemistry preserves the petrochemicals industry that Sasol's Secunda
      complex anchors. Done with discipline, the hydrocarbon bridge buys the
      fifteen-to-twenty-year window during which the green-industrial pillars
      mature; done badly, it locks in stranded assets and emissions exposure
      that the next decade's climate-finance regime will price into sovereign
      borrowing terms. The strategic question is not whether to use the resource
      but on what fiscal, environmental, and downstream- beneficiation terms.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar D — Regional Anchor Strategy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa cannot compete head-on with Asian manufacturing at scale. It
      can be the financial, logistics, and industrial hub of the AfCFTA —
      Johannesburg as Africa's capital market, Durban and Ngqura as container
      gateways, the rail corridor as the connective tissue of SADC trade. The
      comparative advantage is institutional depth and geographic position, not
      labour cost. The regional anchor strategy is the domestic expression of
      the Pan-African Way: continental integration is both developmental and
      security-positive because it enlarges the market for South African output
      and reduces the exposure of SADC economies to extra-regional shocks.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar E — State Capacity Reconstruction Before Expansion
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The developmental-state agenda cannot be advanced through an expansion of
      the state's scope while the existing scope is under-performing. The
      endowment-aligned strategy requires a deliberate sequencing: capacity
      first, expansion second. That means ruthless
      <a
        href="/reform/articles/ra-5-2-anti-capture-architecture"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold"
        >civil-service professionalisation</a
      >, the unbundling and reform of Eskom and Transnet, the repair of the
      revenue authority and the
      <a
        href="/articles/ss-3-2-independent-investigating-magistracy"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold"
        >prosecutorial apparatus</a
      >, and the insulation of technical appointments from political
      interference. Fiscal consolidation is part of the same package, as are
      targeted cash transfers rather than a universal Basic Income Grant — the
      tax base cannot support Nordic ambitions, and pretending otherwise
      produces deficit-financed promises that the next generation cannot honour.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar F — Strategic Non-Alignment as Leverage
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Non-alignment, properly understood, is not an identity but a tool. It is
      valuable to the extent that it generates bargaining leverage with the
      United States and the European Union (market access, AGOA-type deals,
      capital), with China (infrastructure financing, industrial capacity,
      technology transfer), and with BRICS partners (diplomatic weight in forums
      that exclude the West). The endowment-aligned Way uses non-alignment to
      extract concessions from all three, without picking sides publicly, and
      reserves its values-based positioning for cases where the constitutional
      framework requires it. This is not a retreat from the 2011 White Paper; it
      is a disciplining of its application.
    </p>

    <aside
      class="border-l-4 border-red-500 bg-red-50/40 p-5 rounded-r-lg my-8"
      role="note"
      aria-label="What to Give Up"
    >
      <p
        class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-red-700 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2"
      >
        What to Give Up
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-primary leading-relaxed mb-3">
        The prescriptive strategy requires abandoning several positions that
        currently absorb political energy without producing strategic return.
      </p>
      <ul
        class="list-disc list-outside ml-5 space-y-2 text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed"
      >
        <li>
          <strong class="text-text-primary"
            >The broad-spectrum manufacturing-revival fantasy</strong
          >
          — that South Africa can rebuild its 1980s industrial base across every sector
          — has to be let go. Focus is not the same as surrender.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-text-primary"
            >Import-substitution nostalgia</strong
          >, which produced the tariff walls of the apartheid era and the
          inefficiencies they protected, must be distinguished from
          sectoral-targeting strategies aimed at endowment-aligned activity.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-text-primary"
            >The pretence that SOEs can be simultaneously commercial and welfare
            instruments</strong
          > has to end. They are one or the other, and the conflation is the mechanism
          by which both functions deteriorate.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </aside>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Internal Risks to Flag
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The biggest internal risks are specific. The Government of National Unity
      coalition is unstable and its durability determines the reform horizon.
      Patronage networks inside the governing bloc resist SOE reform because SOE
      reform threatens their revenue streams, and the confrontation is political
      rather than merely administrative. The inequality-growth tension produces
      constant pressure for redistribution in excess of what the productive base
      can sustain. None of these risks is unique to South Africa; all have to be
      named as part of a strategy that proposes to act against them. A grand
      strategy that ignores the politics of its own implementation is a
      document, not a plan.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 9: Gap & Synthesis -->
  <section
    id="synthesis"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Gap and synthesis"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 9
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      Bridging the Gap: From Constitutional Non-Alignment to Endowment-Aligned
      Execution
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The argument of the previous sections reaches a specific synthesis: the
      current strategy's architecture is not wrong. Its Ends — the vision, the
      four national interests, the eight NSS pillars — and its Ways — active
      non-alignment, Pan-African agency, Ubuntu values-based entrepreneurship,
      coordinated multi-alignment — together form a broadly coherent doctrinal
      package. The values framework does real work, and the strategic discipline
      of reading security through the constitutional values of dignity,
      equality, and freedom distinguishes South Africa from most peer states.
      The problem is not doctrinal. It is a failure of economic foundation and
      execution priority.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 leading-relaxed">
      Three bridging moves are required to convert the strategy from aspiration
      into plan.
    </p>

    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6"
      aria-label="Three bridging moves"
    >
      {
        bridgingMoves.map((m) => (
          <div class="border-l-4 border-compass-green bg-compass-green-light rounded-r-lg p-4 flex flex-col">
            <span class="font-heading text-xs font-bold text-compass-green uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">
              Move {m.n}
            </span>
            <h3 class="font-heading text-base font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 leading-snug">
              {m.title}
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">{m.body}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The dominant probable trajectory, as Otto and Nagar's scenario work and
      the Belfer Center and ISS analyses all converge in projecting, is
      sustained normative posture with incremental adaptation to external
      pressure and continued drift between stated and executable capability. The
      strategy persists in its current form because each separate institution
      has an incentive to defend its own pillar, and no single institution has
      the authority to impose the triage the synthesis requires. That is itself
      a coordination-deficit outcome, and it is the one the
      <a
        href="/reform/programme"
        class="text-compass-green hover:underline font-semibold"
        >Reform Agenda</a
      >
      articulated across this site is designed to address.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary"
        >The key variable across every scenario is economic recovery. Without
        it, the grand strategy becomes performative — elegantly drafted,
        diplomatically decorated, and quietly unaffordable.</strong
      >
      With it, the architecture that the doctrinal stack already provides becomes
      materially fundable. The next section makes the bridge explicit: how the domestic
      reform programme that GovCompass has articulated across its five pillars is
      the execution layer on which a grand strategy of any kind — current or endowment-aligned
      — must stand.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Alignment Section -->
  <section
    id="alignment"
    class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24"
    aria-label="Alignment with the GovCompass Reform Agenda"
  >
    <p
      class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1"
    >
      Section 10 — The Bridge
    </p>
    <h2
      class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4"
    >
      Alignment with the GovCompass Reform Agenda
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Grand strategy answers the question of what a state seeks and how it
      deploys its instruments. Domestic governance reform answers the question
      of whether the state can actually operate the instruments it claims. The
      two questions are inseparable. A state whose municipalities cannot supply
      clean water, whose provincial education departments cannot staff qualified
      subject advisors, and whose national departments cannot coordinate
      cross-cutting reform cannot execute a national security strategy —
      regardless of how elegantly drafted the doctrine is.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Reform Agenda articulated across GovCompass is the domestic execution
      layer. Every pillar of the Agenda corresponds to a pillar, Way, Mean, or
      risk family of the grand strategy. The correspondences are not
      coincidental. They are structural — the Agenda was designed around the
      RAARICLE™ diagnostic framework that isolates exactly the governance-design
      failures which erode the instruments of national power. The table below
      makes the mapping explicit.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      {
        alignmentMap.map((m) => (
          <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-5 bg-bg-secondary/30">
            <p class="font-heading text-sm font-bold text-compass-green mb-1">
              Grand Strategy — {m.nss}
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3 italic">{m.nssDesc}</p>
            <p class="font-heading text-sm font-bold text-text-primary mb-1">
